&gt; I&#39;m really new to javascript so this the best I could do to actually make a working clock. I&#39;m more familiar with python.

OK, then let&#39;s take it simple and slow

The Stopwatch:
-----

A better approach than counting the seconds, minutes and hours on an interval, and therefore introducing an error with every increment *(the intervals in JS are not accurate)* let&#39;s define the value on the stopwatch as the difference betwen `Date.now()` and somne `startTime`.

This is while the clock is running, we also need to store this `value` while the clock is not running. Before it has started, after it has stopped, ...

```js
var isRunning = false;
var value = 0;
var startTime = 0;

function getValue() {
  return isRunning ? Date.now() - startTime : value;
}
```

`getValue()` returns the number of milliseconds on the clock. That&#39;s all we need to calculate seconds, minutes, hours and days. 

And we are independant of any update-interval. Every time we call the function it will give us an accurate value, wether that&#39;s every frame or once a hour.

Now let&#39;s add the code to start and stop the stopwatch

```js
function start() {
  if (isRunning) return;

  isRunning = true;
  // startTime = Date.now();
  // but we can do better, we can make this function to double as `restart`/`continue`
  startTime = Date.now() - value;
}

function stop() {
  if (!isRunning) return;

  isRunning = false;
  value = Date.now() - startTime;
}

// just resets the (computed) value to 0.
// does not `stop()` the stopwatch if it is running.
function reset() {
  if (isRunning) {
    startTime = Date.now();
  } else {
    value = 0;
  }
}
```

Since `start()` and `stop()` check wether the stopwatch `isRunning` or not, there&#39;s no issue if you call them multiple times.

Rendering / UI:
-----
```js
// leading zero
function lz(value) {
  return (value &lt; 10 ? &quot;0&quot; : &quot;&quot;) + value;
}

function render() {
  var val = getValue(), v = Math.abs(val);

  var sign = val &lt; 0 ? &quot;-&quot;: &quot;&quot;;
  var seconds = Math.floor(v/1000)%60,
      minutes = Math.floor(v/60000)%60,
      hours = Math.floor(v/3600000)%24;

  h1.textContent = sign + lz(hours) + &quot;:&quot; + lz(minutes) + &quot;:&quot; + lz(seconds);
}
```

The simplest would be to just render the value all the time 

```js
setInterval(render, 1000);
``` 
downside is that it renders the same value over and over while the stopwatch is not running. but imo. a neglectable overhead *(at least for one stopwatch at an 1000ms inteval)*

or you have to add/remove the interval on start and stop:

```js
var interval;

function start() {
  // ...
  interval = setInterval(render, 1000);
}

function stop() {
  // ...
  clearInterval(interval);
  render();
}

function reset() {
  // ...
  render();
}
```

